<subSubSection id="7BFFEAD3FFD0A71A0CE0FBD4FDEAA6B6" lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph id="335AB958FFD0A7250CE0FBD4FEDEA21A" blockId="31.[151,604,1079,1140]" box="[151,367,1114,1140]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
(
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFD0A7250CE8FBD4FE9FA21A" box="[159,302,1114,1140]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–61" captionStartId="32.[151,269,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[157,1433,279,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-75@32.[151,1436,271,1917]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 55–61. Leptocera erratica sp.n. (55–57: Argentina, 58: Australia, 59–61: U.S.A.). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (55) lateral; (56) posterior; (57) ventral; (58) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (59) dorsal; (60) spermathecae; (61) ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311890" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311890/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Figs. 55–61</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFD0A7250D4DFBD4FED6A21A" box="[314,359,1114,1140]" captionStart="FIGURES 138–146" captionStartId="70.[151,269,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[172,1412,195,1581]" captionTargetId="figure-168@70.[170,1416,194,1585]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 138–146. Postgonites and aedeagal complex of Leptocera caenosa group. Postgonites of (138) L. aequilimbata (Argentina), (139) L. argentinica sp.n. (Argentina), (140) L. neocurvinervis (Chile), (141) L. erratica sp.n. (South Africa), (142) L. sphaerotheca sp.n. (U.S.A.), (143) L. ellipsipennis (Juan Fernández Is.), (144) L. parallelipennis sp.n. (Juan Fernández Is.), (145) L. cultellipennis (Juan Fernández Is.). Aedeagal complex of (146) L. duplicata (Juan Fernández Is.). bp—basiphallus, dp—distiphallus, ea—ejaculatory apodeme, pa—phallapodeme, pg—postgonites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311916/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">141</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFD0A7250CE0FB29FB68A399" blockId="31.[151,1436,1191,2030]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFD0A7250CE0FB29FE99A2AF" bold="true" box="[151,296,1191,1217]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Description</emphasis>
. Body length 
<quantity id="F41D14BDFFD0A7250DA5FB26FDD2A2AC" box="[466,611,1192,1218]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.7 mm</quantity>
. Coloration similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFD0A7250F18FB26FC41A2AF" baseAuthorityName="Rondani" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[879,1008,1192,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caenosa">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFD0A7250F18FB26FC41A2AF" box="[879,1008,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">L. caenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with pale elements usually slightly more developed: Medium brown with anterior part of frons, lower part of face (sometimes), inner surfaces of pedicel and first flagellomere and part of gena more or less yellow to reddish; palpus, inner surface of fore coxa, mid trochanter, knees, apices of tibiae, base of fore tibia and tarsi pale brown. Uppermost orbital setula inclinate and proclinate (sometimes absent on one side). Arista long-pubescent (as in 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFD0A72508D8FACDFA83A332" baseAuthorityName="Rondani" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[1199,1330,1347,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caenosa">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFD0A72508D8FACDFA83A332" box="[1199,1330,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">L. caenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Palpus inflated (even slightly more than in 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFD0A7250E35FAE7FD73A3EC" baseAuthorityName="Rondani" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[578,706,1385,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caenosa">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFD0A7250E35FAE7FD73A3EC" box="[578,706,1385,1410]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">L. caenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), ca. 3.5x as long as wide. Mid tibia with bristle above distal dorsal about 0.4–0.6x as long as distal anterodorsal bristle; lowermost bristle of proximal posterodorsal series shorter than lowermost bristle of anterodorsal series; posteroapical bristles short and usually of equal length, ventral one sometimes longer. Segments 3–5 of fore tarsus dilated in male, normal in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFD0A7250CB0F98AFE44A114" blockId="31.[151,1436,1191,2030]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Male terminalia (
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFD0A7250DE1F98AFD98A070" box="[406,553,1540,1566]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–61" captionStartId="32.[151,269,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[157,1433,279,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-75@32.[151,1436,271,1917]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 55–61. Leptocera erratica sp.n. (55–57: Argentina, 58: Australia, 59–61: U.S.A.). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (55) lateral; (56) posterior; (57) ventral; (58) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (59) dorsal; (60) spermathecae; (61) ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311890" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311890/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Figs. 55–58</figureCitation>
): Sternite 5 with few long bristles posterolaterally; posteromedial field of microtrichia fairly narrow, subtriangular; hind margin with short and very fine, hair-like scales (somewhat overemphasized in 
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFD0A7250DFEF9DFFE56A005" box="[393,487,1617,1643]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–61" captionStartId="32.[151,269,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[157,1433,279,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-75@32.[151,1436,271,1917]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 55–61. Leptocera erratica sp.n. (55–57: Argentina, 58: Australia, 59–61: U.S.A.). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (55) lateral; (56) posterior; (57) ventral; (58) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (59) dorsal; (60) spermathecae; (61) ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311890" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311890/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
). Epandrium with relatively few long bristles ventrally. Anterior section of surstylus with anterior process extending far ventrally, laterally with a subtle ridge terminating in a darker, preapical, anteriorly directed point; ventral lobe nearly flat and almost bristleless, its long posterior bristle shifted forward and greatly removed from hind margin. Posterior section of surstylus of roughly triangular shape (posterior view), inner margin only very narrowly desclerotized (unlike most South American species), apex with two strong bristles (both with pointed tips), posterior surface with few long pale hairs in lateral half. Cercus simple (i.e., without finger-like or lamellate medial process). Postgonite with wide and shallow posterobasal notch (
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFD0A7250DF5F8EEFE59A114" box="[386,488,1888,1914]" captionStart="FIGURES 138–146" captionStartId="70.[151,269,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[172,1412,195,1581]" captionTargetId="figure-168@70.[170,1416,194,1585]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 138–146. Postgonites and aedeagal complex of Leptocera caenosa group. Postgonites of (138) L. aequilimbata (Argentina), (139) L. argentinica sp.n. (Argentina), (140) L. neocurvinervis (Chile), (141) L. erratica sp.n. (South Africa), (142) L. sphaerotheca sp.n. (U.S.A.), (143) L. ellipsipennis (Juan Fernández Is.), (144) L. parallelipennis sp.n. (Juan Fernández Is.), (145) L. cultellipennis (Juan Fernández Is.). Aedeagal complex of (146) L. duplicata (Juan Fernández Is.). bp—basiphallus, dp—distiphallus, ea—ejaculatory apodeme, pa—phallapodeme, pg—postgonites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311916/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 141</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFD0A71A0CB0F808FDEAA6B6" blockId="31.[151,1436,1191,2030]" lastBlockId="32.[151,1435,152,216]" lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Female terminalia (
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFD0A7250DC4F808FDF6A1CE" box="[435,583,1926,1952]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–61" captionStartId="32.[151,269,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[157,1433,279,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-75@32.[151,1436,271,1917]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 55–61. Leptocera erratica sp.n. (55–57: Argentina, 58: Australia, 59–61: U.S.A.). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (55) lateral; (56) posterior; (57) ventral; (58) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (59) dorsal; (60) spermathecae; (61) ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311890" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311890/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Figs. 59–61</figureCitation>
): Tergite 7 moderately long and convex (length smaller than in South American species), with a pair of strong, cruciate bristles near middle, apparently tomentose throughout and lacking shining areas. Sternite 7 with simple hind margin. Fused tergite 10 + cerci moderately short (longer than in South American species), with short hairs. Spermathecae elongate, with transversely ridged basal half and slightly dilated, bumpy distal half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
